excerpt: This reconstructed castle, originally completed in 1607, sits atop a hill & houses a history museum.
detail_description: Kumamoto Castle, originally built in 1607, is a reconstructed castle located in the heart of Kumamoto City. It serves as a history museum and stands as a symbol of the city's rich heritage. The castle played a significant role during Japan's Warring States period and continues to be an integral part of Kumamoto's identity.
name: Kumamoto Castle

excerpt: This tranquil garden features traditional Japanese landscaping & historic landmarks in miniature.
detail_description: Suizenji Jojuen Garden is a serene and picturesque Japanese landscape garden located in Kumamoto. It was originally constructed by the renowned Hosokawa family during the 17th century and has since been opened to the public as a tranquil park. The garden features meticulously designed miniature landmarks, including small rolling hills and a replica of Mount Fuji. Visitors can also enjoy attractions such as a tea house, a large pond, traditional Noh theater performances, and occasional horse archery tournaments.
name: Suizenji Jojuen
address: 8-1 Suizenji Koen, Chuo Ward, Kumamoto, 862-0956, Japan

excerpt: Popular tourist district with an expansive shopping arcade, restaurants & cafes & cultural exhibits.
detail_description: Sakura-no-baba Josaien is a vibrant tourist district located in the Sakuranobaba area of Kumamoto Castle. It features an extensive shopping arcade, numerous restaurants and cafes, and cultural exhibits that showcase Kumamoto's rich history and heritage.
name: Sakura-no-baba Josaien

excerpt: Kumamoto is a city on the Japanese island of Kyushu. Kumamoto Castle dates back to the 17th century. On the castle grounds is the reconstructed Honmaru Goten Palace with its ornate reception rooms and murals. Kumamoto Prefectural Museum of Art shows both European works and Edo-period prints. Southeast of the city center is Suizenji Garden, a Japanese landscape garden with a central pond, created in the 1630s.
detail_description: Kumamoto, a city located on the Japanese island of Kyushu, is known for its historical sites and cultural attractions. The 17th-century Kumamoto Castle and the reconstructed Honmaru Goten Palace are popular landmarks within the city. Visitors can also explore the Kumamoto Prefectural Museum of Art, which showcases European works and Edo-period prints. For a serene experience, Suizenji Garden offers a tranquil setting with its Japanese landscape garden featuring a central pond.
name: Kumamoto

detail_description: Reigando Cave, situated in Kumamoto, Japan, is a place of great historical and cultural significance. It holds the distinction of being where the renowned samurai Miyamoto Musashi wrote the final chapter of 'The Book of Five Rings.' Nestled on the western side of Mount Kimpo, this natural cave offers visitors a tranquil atmosphere and a chance to explore the space where Musashi spent his last days.
name: Reigando Cave
address: Matsuomachi Hirayama, Nishi Ward, Kumamoto, 861-5282, Japan

excerpt: Modern art center showcasing a diverse collection of local & international works & cultural events.
detail_description: The Contemporary Art Museum Kumamoto is a vibrant hub for modern art, showcasing a diverse collection of local and international works. The museum hosts cultural events and special exhibitions, including the current showcase of Tatsuya Tanaka's whimsical miniature photography. Visitors can expect thought-provoking installations and interactive displays that offer a refreshing perspective on contemporary art.
name: Contemporary Art Museum Kumamoto

excerpt: Tourist shop with a brown bear mascot offering local information, regional products & food.
detail_description: Kumamon Square is the ultimate destination for fans of Kumamon, the lovable brown bear mascot of Kumamoto prefecture. This tourist shop offers a wide range of local information, regional products, and delicious food. Visitors can browse through an array of original Kumamon-themed goods and may even have the chance to meet the famous mascot in person if they check his schedule on the official website.
name: Kumamon Square
address: テトリアくまもとビル 1階, 8-2 Tetorihoncho, Chuo Ward, Kumamoto, 860-0808, Japan

excerpt: Museum featuring regional antique art & sculpture, along with classical European paintings.
detail_description: The Kumamoto Prefectural Museum of Art Main Building, located in Nimaru Park near Kumamoto Castle, is a must-visit for art enthusiasts. Opened in 1976, the museum showcases a diverse range of exhibits including ancient Japanese art, modern pieces, archaeology, painting, printmaking, sculpture and craftsmanship. Visitors can admire regional antique art alongside classical European paintings. The museum also features international works by renowned artists such as Renoir and Rodin.
name: Kumamoto Prefectural Museum of Art Main Building

excerpt: Kumamoto is a prefecture in the central part of Japan’s southwestern Kyushu island. Its natural features include many active volcanoes, river rapids and hot spring spas. The capital city of Kumamoto is home to Kumamoto Castle, originally built in the 17th century. Other sites dating to the 17th century include Suizenji Jojuen, a traditional Japanese garden, and Hosokawa Mansion, a former samurai residence.
detail_description: Kumamoto, a prefecture in Japan's Kyushu island, is known for its natural beauty, including active volcanoes and hot spring spas. The capital city boasts historical sites like Kumamoto Castle and Suizenji Jojuen garden. Referred to as the Land of Fire due to Mt. Aso, it offers stunning coastal views at Okoshiki beach and is famous for Kuma Shochu, a rice-based spirit.
name: Kumamoto

detail_description: The Kumamoto Prefectural Traditional Crafts Center is a showcase of local handicrafts, featuring traditional metalwork, ceramics, woodwork, bamboo crafts, dyeing and weaving, paper products, and traditional toys. Visitors can explore the creative output of generations of local artisans. However, it's important to note that the items are for sale and may be on the pricier side. The center is not recommended for young children who may have trouble resisting touching the delicate crafts.
name: Kumamoto Prefectural Traditional Crafts Center

detail_description: Kokutei is a renowned ramen shop located in Nishi Ward, Kumamoto City, offering a delectable variety of Kumamoto ramen. The shop takes pride in producing its own medium-thick and perfectly textured noodles, as well as the chashu pork. One of their signature elements is the fragrant charred garlic oil that adds a slightly bitter yet aromatic flavor to the dish.
name: Kumamoto Ramen KOKUTEI Honten (Main Store)
address: 2 Chome-1-23 Nihongi, Nishi Ward, Kumamoto, 860-0051, Japan

detail_description: In Kumamoto City, the Shimada Museum of Art is a must-visit destination for those interested in immersing themselves in the region's rich history and culture. Nestled within a serene bamboo forest, this museum showcases Kumamoto's arts and crafts from the Momoyama-Edo period, along with historical relics and ancient artworks that reflect the area's deep-rooted warrior culture.
name: Shimada Museum
address: 4 Chome-5-28 Shimasaki, Nishi Ward, Kumamoto, 860-0073, Japan

detail_description: Fujisaki Hachimangu Shrine is a prominent shrine located in the Chuo Ward of Kumamoto City. It serves as the main shrine of Kumamoto and is frequented by many locals. Visitors can take the Sendai sightseeing bus loople to reach the shrine, which takes about 20 minutes from getting off to leaving. The shrine opens around 9 a.m. on weekdays, offering a serene atmosphere with fewer tourists and employees cleaning the premises.
name: Fujisaki Hachimangu

detail_description: Kumamoto Station is a modern and efficient transportation hub located in Kumamoto City, Japan. It serves as a central point for both local commuters and tourists exploring the region. The station's sleek and spacious design offers a comfortable environment for travelers. Nearby, the City Tram provides easy access to major destinations such as Kumamoto Castle and Suizenji Jojuen Garden, making it convenient for tourists to get around the city.
name: Kumamoto Station
address: 3 Chome-15-1 Kasuga, Nishi Ward, Kumamoto, 860-0047, Japan

excerpt: Cozy, historic Shinto shrine boasting views of Kumamoto Castle.
detail_description: Katō Shrine is a historic Shinto shrine dedicated to Kiyomasa Katō, a prominent warlord of the Warring States period who played a significant role in building Kumamoto Castle and establishing the city's foundation. It is quite rare to find a shrine in Japan that venerates an actual historical figure, highlighting the close relationship between Kiyomasa and Kumamoto.
name: Katō Shrine

excerpt: Tranquil gardens & zoo, featuring over a thousand animals & a wide variety of plants & flowers.
detail_description: Kumamoto City Zoo and Botanical Garden is a serene oasis featuring a diverse collection of over a thousand animals and an extensive variety of plants and flowers. The zoo offers a compact layout, making it ideal for families with young children to explore without getting too tired. Additionally, there are rides for small children and reasonably priced refreshments available within the zoo grounds. Situated on the picturesque edge of Ezu Lake, this attraction provides an enjoyable escape from historical sites like castles and temples.
name: Kumamoto City Zoo and Botanical Garden
address: 5 Chome-14-2 Kengun, Higashi Ward, Kumamoto, 862-0911, Japan

excerpt: 1614 Buddhist temple complex, known for its 176 stone steps leading to the grave of Katō Kiyomasa.
detail_description: Honmyoji is a historic Buddhist temple complex located in Kumamoto, known for its serene and spiritual atmosphere. The temple is situated on a hillside, accessible via a picturesque staircase of 176 stone steps lined with lanterns. It was completed in 1614 and is home to the grave of Katō Kiyomasa, a prominent figure in the construction of Kumamoto Castle.
name: Honmyoji
address: 4 Chome-13-1 Hanazono, Nishi Ward, Kumamoto, 860-0072, Japan

detail_description: Kumamoto City Hall may not seem like a must-see attraction, but it offers free access to an observation deck on the fourteenth floor that provides stunning views of the city, including the iconic Kumamoto Castle. Visitors can enjoy photo opportunities and panoramic vistas of downtown Kumamoto from this vantage point. Despite being a government building rather than a tourist spot, tourists are welcome to visit without any formalities or fees. The friendly and accommodating staff further enhance the experience.
name: Kumamoto City Hall

detail_description: Aso Kumamoto Airport is a convenient gateway to the Kyushu region, offering easy access to cities like Hiroshima, Fukuoka, Nagasaki, and Kagoshima. Upon arrival in the city center, travelers can hop on the Kumamoto City Tram for a picturesque journey through the heart of the action. This affordable mode of transportation provides a charming way to explore the city while avoiding urban traffic.
name: Kumamoto Airport
address: 1802-2 Oyatsu, Mashiki, Kamimashiki District, Kumamoto 861-2204, Japan

excerpt: A glass roof tops this elevated, 511-m.-long shopping corridor with 175 stores & cafes.
detail_description: Shimotori Shopping Arcade is a bustling commercial corridor in Kumamoto, featuring 175 stores and cafes under a glass roof. Divided into Kamitori and Shimotori sections, this 511-meter-long arcade offers a wide range of shopping options including fashion, general goods, and recreational facilities. Visitors can also explore numerous dining venues, bars, and after-dark entertainment options nearby.
name: Shimotori Shopping Arcade
address: 1 Chome-3-10 Shimotori, Chuo Ward, Kumamoto, 860-0807, Japan

detail_description: Suizenji Park, also known as Suizenji Jojuen Garden, is a stunning Japanese strolling garden located in Kumamoto, Japan. Constructed in the 17th century by the Hosokawa clan, it features artificial hills and a large central pond fed by natural spring water. The park recreates miniature versions of the 53 post stations along the Tokaido Road from Kyoto to Edo during the Edo period.
name: Suizenji Park
address: 8-1 Suizenji Koen, Chuo Ward, Kumamoto, 862-0956, Japan

detail_description: Hanaokayama, located near the train station in Kumamoto, offers a picturesque 15-minute trek up the hill to reach a small shrine and breathtaking panoramic views of the city. The hill is particularly enchanting in the evening when the city lights twinkle below, creating a dreamy and romantic atmosphere. While it's an easy hike, visitors can also drive up to enjoy the stunning vistas.
name: Hanaokayama

detail_description: Situated in the heart of Kumamoto, Japan, the Kumamoto City Museum is a captivating destination for history buffs and culture lovers. The museum's contemporary building houses an extensive array of artifacts, exhibits, and interactive displays that offer a deep dive into the region's rich heritage spanning centuries. Recently revamped with a focus on Kumamoto Castle, it now features more kid-friendly exhibits making it an ideal stop for families.
name: Kumamoto City Museum

excerpt: Park with 2 swimming lakes fed by underground springs, known for water birds, fishing & boat rental.
detail_description: Ezu Lake is a picturesque spot located in the center of Kumamoto city, known for its beautiful scenery and cultural significance. The lake runs alongside route 57 and offers activities such as swimming, fishing, and boat rental. It is fed by underground springs like the Shirakawa river source and Kikuchi river source, making it a sightseeing attraction due to the raw power of these natural springs.
name: Ezu Lake
address: 3 Chome-11-8 Koto, Higashi Ward, Kumamoto, 862-0942, Japan

excerpt: Park around placid Ezu Lake, with a jogging circuit, plus rowing & pedal boats for rental.
detail_description: Suizenji Ezuko Park is a vast and picturesque green space located in Kumamoto-shi, offering a variety of activities for visitors. The park features Ezu Lake, where you can relax and observe waterfowl or rent paddle boats to explore the serene waters. In the evening, you can enjoy the sight of fireflies and listen to the chirping insects as the sun sets.
name: Suizenji Ezuko park

detail_description: Former Hosokawa Gyobu Residence, once home to a branch of the influential Hosokawa Clan, showcases the opulent lifestyle of high-ranking samurai families in ancient Japan. Built in 1646, this 900-square-meter mansion boasts a grand Chinese-style entrance and exquisite gardens that are especially stunning during the autumn foliage. Visitors can also partake in a traditional Japanese tea ceremony at the Kiyutei tea house on the premises.
name: Former Hosokawa Gyobu Residence

excerpt: Yamaga is a city in Kumamoto Prefecture, Japan. As of 31 July 2024, the city had an estimated population of 48,181 in 21996 households, and a population density of 160 persons per km². The total area of the city is 299.69 km². Wikipedia.
detail_description: Yamaga, a city in Kumamoto Prefecture, Japan, has a rich history and cultural heritage. Established in 1954, it expanded in 2005 by absorbing several towns. Once a prominent stop on the Buzen Kaido route, it thrived as a prosperous rice center. Today, visitors can admire well-preserved wooden buildings, ancient warehouses, sake breweries, and rice dealers' shops that exude the Edo Period atmosphere.
name: Yamaga

detail_description: Tsuruya Department Store, a long-standing establishment in Kumamoto since 1952, maintains its classic exterior while housing one of the largest shopping floors in the country. It prides itself on offering a high-quality and elegant lifestyle through locally-rooted shops and products. The store features a wide range of high-quality items from fashion to food, as well as a food court on the basement floor and restaurants on the 7th floor.
name: Tsuruya Department Store

detail_description: Sumiyoshi Nature Park is a picturesque destination, especially during the hydrangea season in mid-June. The park offers a serene atmosphere with its stunning views of the sea and a charming torii gate. Visitors can explore the shrine located atop the hill, where they can draw fortunes. The area is adorned with colorful hydrangeas, creating a beautiful sight for photography enthusiasts and nature lovers alike. While navigating through the park, visitors should be cautious of steep and mossy stairs.
name: Sumiyoshi Nature Park

detail_description: Lafcadio Hearn's Former Residence is a historical site located in Kumamoto, Japan. It was the home of Lafcadio Hearn, a Greek writer known for his writings on Japanese supernatural folklore and ghosts. During his 14-year stay in Japan, he fully immersed himself in the culture, even adopting a Japanese name and lifestyle. His works such as Glimpses of Unfamiliar Japan and Kwaidan: Stories and Studies of Strange Things continue to captivate readers today.
name: Lafcadio Hearn's Former Residence

detail_description: Tatsuda Nature Park, nestled in the northeastern part of Kumamoto City, is a serene and picturesque destination. Originally loaned to the city by the Hosokawa family, it has become a beloved retreat for locals. The park's historical significance as the burial ground of the Hosokawa lords led to its designation as a National Historic Site. Despite its somewhat hidden location behind Kumamoto University, this tranquil park offers visitors an opportunity to immerse themselves in nature without crowds.
name: Tatsuda Nature Park
address: 4 Chome-610 Kurokami, Chuo Ward, Kumamoto, 860-0862, Japan

detail_description: Aqua Dome Kumamoto is a popular destination for both leisure and sports activities. It offers a variety of facilities, including swimming pools that are perfect for teaching life-saving techniques to children from an early age. The venue also transforms into a skating rink during the winter season, providing entertainment for families with kids. Additionally, it has hosted water polo events and is praised as a great location for such competitions. Visitors have also enjoyed the gym facilities available at Aqua Dome Kumamoto.
name: Aqua Dome Kumamoto
address: 2 Chome-1-1 Arao, Minami Ward, Kumamoto, 861-4136, Japan

excerpt: Modern 4-story art museum with unique architecture, housing local art & crafts, plus a coffee shop.
detail_description: Kumamoto Prefectural Museum of Art Chibajo Branch is a modern 4-story art museum with unique architecture, showcasing local art and crafts. It also features a cafe on the 4th floor offering a stunning view of Kumamoto Castle. The museum hosts various exhibitions each week, ensuring visitors always have something new to explore. Additionally, there's a library on the first floor with art-related books available for browsing.
name: Kumamoto Prefectural Museum of Art Chibajo Branch

detail_description: Nagabeta Seabed Road is a unique undersea pathway that emerges during low tide and disappears beneath the sea during high tide, leaving only the utility poles visible. Constructed in 1974 by local fishermen for cultivating seaweed and shellfish in the Ariake Sea, this enigmatic road has become a popular photography spot in Kumamoto.
name: Nagabeta Seabed Road

detail_description: The Statue of Kato Kiyomasa stands proudly in front of Kumamoto Castle, paying homage to the first feudal lord of Kumamoto and the mastermind behind the castle's design. Dressed in armor and a distinctive crow's-bonnet, the statue depicts Kiyomasa Kato, who is celebrated for his castle building skills and water management projects. Visitors can learn about his influential designs while admiring this iconic landmark before entering Kumamoto Castle.
name: Statue of Kato Kiyomasa

excerpt: Colorful Inari shrine offering water fortunes, plus a circle of wisdom & souvenirs.
detail_description: Kumamoto Castle Inari Shrine is a lovely local shrine located near the entrance of Kumamoto Castle. It offers colorful Inari shrines, protective charms, and fortune papers. Visitors can also obtain beautiful goshuincho here. The shrine has a mixture of traditional elements from before the Meiji era, combining both Kami and Buddha in the same complex.
name: Kumamoto Castle Inari Shrine

excerpt: Reconstructed Shinto temple & shrine, damaged in WWII, offering worship, festivals & ceremonies.
detail_description: Izumi Shrine is a reconstructed Shinto temple and shrine that was damaged during World War II. The park surrounding it also features a Noh theater, a guest room from the Kyoto Imperial Palace, and a garden adorned with cherry blossoms, pine trees, ponds, stones, and an artificial hill resembling Mt. Visitors can partake in worship, festivals, and ceremonies at the shrine.
name: Izumi Shrine
address: 8-1 Suizenji Koen, Chuo Ward, Kumamoto, 862-0956, Japan

detail_description: Kengun Shrine is a significant landmark in Kumamoto City, known for its rich history and welcoming atmosphere. As one of the oldest shrines in the city, it holds a special place in the hearts of locals and visitors alike. The shrine offers a glimpse into traditional Japanese culture and provides an opportunity for prayer and reflection. Visitors can also enjoy interacting with the friendly family who oversees the shrine, as they are eager to share its history.
name: Kengun Shrine

detail_description: Tabaruzaka Park is a historical site in Kumamoto, known for being the location of the intense battle during the Seinan Rebellion. The park features a cenotaph, museum, and a warehouse with restored bullet holes from old photographs. The museum provides detailed insights into the war centered around Tabaruzaka, offering a neutral perspective on this significant event in Japan's history. Despite its historical significance, the park now offers serene and relaxing scenery for cherry blossom viewing and picnics.
name: Tabaruzaka Park
address: Japan, 〒861-0163 Kumamoto, Kita Ward, Uekimachi Toyooka, 字舟底８５８−１外

name: Kokai Park
address: 2 Chome-32-21 Kurokami, Chuo Ward, Kumamoto, 860-0862, Japan

detail_description: Kumamoto Daijingu Shrine is a small and serene shrine with relatively few visitors. Despite its modest size, it enshrines Amaterasu Omikami and Toyouke Omikami, similar to the renowned Ise Shrine. The shrine's gambrel-style building is quite spacious and stylish, with an impressive large front gable that exudes a cool vibe.
name: Kumamoto Daijingu Shrine

detail_description: Egao Kenko Stadium is a popular venue for live football and rugby matches. Visitors recommend arriving an hour early due to crowded parking and seating. Bringing your own food and snacks is suggested as the onsite options can be expensive. Despite its open design, the stadium offers a quaint and enjoyable atmosphere for watching sports events. The friendly staff add to the overall positive experience at this well-organized venue in Japan.
name: Egao Kenko Stadium

detail_description: The Tabaruzaka Satsuma Rebellion Museum is located on the historic battleground of the Southwestern Rebellion. The museum features a bullet mark house that allows visitors to see the intensity of the battlefield during the Seinan affair. The castle, heavily damaged during the Satsuma Rebellion in 1877, underwent significant reconstructions in 1960 and further restorations after the 2016 Kumamoto Earthquake.
name: Tabaruzaka Satsuma Rebellion Museum
address: 858-1 Uekimachi Toyooka, Kita Ward, Kumamoto, 861-0163, Japan

name: Janes Residence
address: 12-10 Suizenji Koen, Chuo Ward, Kumamoto, 862-0956, Japan

detail_description: Tetori Catholic Church, a stunning place of worship situated on sacred and fortunate land, boasts an amiable and affable clergyman named Father John. The establishment also features a charming boutique filled with delightful treasures. Sunday services are held at both 9am and 11am, providing parishioners with multiple opportunities to attend mass. Additionally, there is a weekly Japanese mass at the fixed time of 10:00.
name: Tetori Catholic Church

detail_description: Natsume Soseki Former Residence is a must-visit attraction in Kumamoto. The area features footpaths that were the inspiration for Soseki's novel "Kusamakura" (The Three-cornered World). Toge-no-Chaya Park, mentioned in the book, can also be explored. The residence has been restored and offers a glimpse into the life of this renowned Japanese author.
name: Natsume Soseki Former Residence

detail_description: Kitaoka Shrine is the first Gion shrine in Kyushu, situated at the base of Mt. Hanaoka near JR Kumamoto Station. The shrine features a 1-year-old shinboku couple Kusunoki in Omotesando, believed to bring benefits for marriage and happy couples. It was built in 934 and is known for its historical significance.
name: Kitaoka Shrine
address: 1 Chome-8-16 Kasuga, Nishi Ward, Kumamoto, 860-0047, Japan

detail_description: Wakuwakuza, Kumamotojo museum offers a variety of ways to learn about the history and significance of Kumamoto Castle. The second floor features a VR theater showcasing 3D images of the castle before it was damaged by an earthquake, along with videos detailing its history and defensive features. The museum also delves into the Satsuma rebellion and the aftermath of the 2016 earthquake through interactive exhibits and videos.
name: Kumamoto Castle Museum Wakuwakuza

detail_description: Memorial Park is a charming spot where cherry blossoms bloom early, marking the onset of spring. The beautiful cherry blossoms make it an ideal location for a delightful lunch. Visitors can also find amenities such as flush toilets and benches, although there is no designated parking area available on-site.
name: Memorial Park
address: 1 Chome-114-1 Kamisuizenji, Chuo Ward, Kumamoto, 862-0951, Japan

detail_description: Musashizuka Park, located on the Ozu Kaido highway, is a serene memorial to the legendary samurai Miyamoto Musashi. The park features rows of ancient cedar trees and a mossy tombstone marking Musashi's burial site, where he was laid to rest in armor with a sword as per his last wishes. A bronze statue of Musashi and a stone pagoda dedicated to the master swordsman can also be found within the park.
name: Musashizuka Park
address: 1 Chome-1232 Tatsudamachi Yuge, Kita Ward, Kumamoto, 861-8007, Japan
